e.\n2. For multiple-bit signals displayed in HEX format, also display the BINARY format if its width <= 64.\n\n\n\nTry to understand the requirements above and give reasoning steps in natural language to achieve it.\nIn addition, try to give advice to avoid syntax error.\nAn SystemVerilog module always starts with a line starting with the keyword \'module\' followed by the module name.\nIt ends with the keyword \'endmodule\'.\n\nBelow is the golden testbench code for the module generated with the given natural language specification.\n<golden_testbench>\n`timescale 1 ps/1 ps\n`define OK 12\n`define INCORRECT 13\n\n\nmodule stimulus_gen (\n\tinput clk,\n\toutput logic in1, in2\n);\n\n\tinitial begin\n\t\trepeat(100) @(posedge clk, negedge clk) begin\n\t\t\t{in1, in2} <= $random;\n\t\tend\n\t\t\n\t\t#1 $finish;\n\tend\n\t\nendmodule\n\nmodule tb();\n\n\ttypedef struct packed {\n\t\tint errors;\n\t\tint errortime;\n\t\tint errors_out;\n\t\tint errortime_out;\n\n\t\tint clocks;\n\t} stats;\n\t\n\tstats stats1;\n\t\n\t\n\twire[511:0] wavedrom_title;\n\twire wavedrom_enable;\n\tint wavedrom_hide_after_time;\n\t\n\treg clk=0;\n\tinitial forever\n\t\t#5 clk = ~clk;\n\n\tlogic in1;\n\tlogic in2;\n\tlogic out_ref;\n\tlogic out_dut;\n\n\tinitial begin \n\t\t$dumpfile("wave.vcd");\n\t\t$dumpvars(1, stim1.clk, tb_mismatch ,in1,in2,out_ref,out_dut );\n\tend\n\n\n\twire tb_match;\t\t// Verification\n\twire tb_mismatch = ~tb_match;\n\t\n\tstimulus_gen stim1 (\n\t\t.clk,\n\t\t.* ,\n\t\t.in1,\n\t\t.in2 );\n\tRefModule good1 (\n\t\t.in1,\n\t\t.in2,\n\t\t.out(out_ref) );\n\t\t\n\tTopModule top_module1 (\n\t\t.in1,\n\t\t.in2,\n\t\t.out(out_dut) );\n\n\t\n\tbit strobe = 0;\n\ttask wait_for_end_of_timestep;\n\t\trepeat(5) begin\n\t\t\tstrobe <= !strobe;  // Try to delay until the very end of the time step.\n\t\t\t@(strobe);\n\t\tend\n\tendtask\t\n\n\t\n\tfinal begin\n\t\tif (stats1.errors_out) $display("Hint: Output \'%s\' has %0d mismatches. First mismatch occurred at time %0d.", "out", stats1.errors_out, stats1.errortime_out);\n\t\telse $display("Hint: Output \'%s\' has no mismatches.", "out");\n\n\t\t$display("Hint: Total mismatched samples is %1d out of %1d samples\\n", stats1.errors, stats1.clocks);\n\t\t$display("Simulation finished at %0d ps", $time);\n\t\t$display("Mismatches: %1d in %1d samples", stats1.errors, stats1.clocks);\n\tend\n\t\n\t// Verification: XORs on the right makes any X in good_vector match anything, but X in dut_vector will only match X.\n\tassign tb_match = ( { out_ref } === ( { out_ref } ^ { out_dut } ^ { out_ref } ) );\n\t// Use explicit sensitivity list here. @(*) causes NetProc::nex_input() to be called when trying to compute\n\t// the sensitivity list of the @(strobe) process, which isn\'t implemented.\n\talways @(posedge clk, negedge clk) begin\n\n\t\tstats1.clocks++;\n\t\tif (!tb_match) begin\n\t\t\tif (stats1.errors == 0) stats1.errortime = $time;\n\t\t\tstats1.errors++;\n\t\tend\n\t\tif (out_ref !== ( out_ref ^ out_dut ^ out_ref ))\n\t\tbegin if (stats1.errors_out == 0) stats1.errortime_out = $time;\n\t\t\tstats1.errors_out = stats1.errors_out+1\'b1; end\n\n\tend\n\n   // add timeout after 100K cycles\n   initial begin\n     #1000000\n     $display("TIMEOUT");\n     $finish();\n   end\n\nendmodule\n\n\n<golden_testbench>\n')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.ASSISTANT: 'assistant'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='{\n    "reasoning": "The goal is to implement the `TopModule` based on the `input_spec` and then significantly enhance the provided `golden_testbench` to meet specific reporting requirements while preserving its core functionality and structure.\\n\\n**1. TopModule Implementation:**\\nThe `input_spec` requires `TopModule` with inputs `in1`, `in2` (1-bit) and output `out` (1-bit). The logic is: `out = in1 & (~in2)` (AND gate with a bubble on `in2`).\\n\\n**2. Interface Derivation:**\\nThe provided `golden_testbench` instantiates `TopModule` with ports `in1`, `in2`, and `out`. Although the `input_spec` only defines the DUT, the testbench uses stimulus generators and reference modules which imply the actual required interface. I must strictly follow the interface implied by the testbench/specification for the DUT itself, which is: `module TopModule(input in1, input in2, output out);` (Using `logic` type as per modern SystemVerilog/testbench style, though the spec implies standard Verilog types).\\n\\n**3. Testbench Improvement:**\\nThe improvements involve modifying the `final` block and the mismatch detection logic within the `always @(posedge clk, negedge clk)` block to adhere to the strict reporting requirements:\\n    a. **Maintain Original Functionality:** The structure, stimulus generation (`stimulus_gen`), reference module (`RefModule`), and timing logic must remain.\\n    b. **Error Reporting:** Replace the existing `Hint` displays in `final` with the required success/failure message.\\n    c. **Mismatch Detail:** When the *first* mismatch occurs (both for `tb_match` and `errors_out`), I must capture and display the inputs (`in1`, `in2`), outputs (`out_dut`, `out_ref`), and expected outputs at that time.\\n    d. **Display Formatting:** For multi-bit signals (though here all signals are 1-bit, the requirement implies readiness for larger signals), display HEX and BINARY if width <= 64.\\n\\n**Implementation Details for Display:**\\nI will introduce a new task or block within the main loop/error handling to print the state upon first mismatch. Since the mismatch logic is intertwined, I will enhance the check inside the `always` block.\\n\\n**Refining the Mismatch Logic:**\\nThe original testbench had two mismatch flags: `tb_match` (for reference vs DUT) and `errors_out` (which seems redundant or specific to a different check). I must ensure the *first* occurrence of *any* mismatch is captured for the final report.\\n\\nI will modify the logic to capture the state when `!tb_match` happens for the first time, and use this for the 